
TY  - JOUR
T1  - 2003 Lawrence R. Klein Lecture  The Case Against Intellectual Monopoly*
AU  - Boldrin, Michele
AU  - Levine, David K.
Y1  - 2004/05/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2004.00128.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 327
EP  - 350
VL  - 45
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2004.00128.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In the modern theory of growth, monopoly plays a crucial role both as a cause and an effect of innovation. Innovative firms, it is argued, would have insufficient incentive to innovate should the prospect of monopoly power not be present. This theme of monopoly runs throughout the theory of growth, international trade, and industrial organization. We argue that monopoly is neither needed for, nor a necessary consequence of innovation. In particular, intellectual property is not necessary for, and may hurt more than help, innovation and growth. We argue that, as a practical matter, it is more likely to hurt.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Comparing Sunspot Equilibrium And Lottery Equilibrium Allocations: The Finite Case*
AU  - Garratt, Rod
AU  - Keister, Todd
AU  - Shell, Karl
Y1  - 2004/05/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2004.00129.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 351
EP  - 386
VL  - 45
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2004.00129.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Sunspot equilibrium and lottery equilibrium are two stochastic solution concepts for nonstochastic economies. We compare these concepts in a class of completely finite, (possibly) nonconvex exchange economies with perfect markets, which requires extending the lottery model to the finite case. Every equilibrium allocation of our lottery model is also a sunspot equilibrium allocation. The converse is almost always true. There are exceptions, however: For some economies, there exist sunspot equilibrium allocations with no lottery equilibrium counterpart.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Market Sharing Agreements and Collusive Networks*
AU  - Belleflamme, Paul
AU  - Bloch, Francis
Y1  - 2004/05/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2004.00130.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 387
EP  - 411
VL  - 45
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2004.00130.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We analyze reciprocal market sharing agreements by which firms commit not to enter each other's territory in oligopolistic markets and procurement auctions. The set of market sharing agreements defines a collusive network. We characterize stable collusive networks when firms and markets are symmetric. Stable networks are formed of complete alliances, of different sizes, larger than a minimal threshold. Typically, stable networks display fewer agreements than the optimal network for the industry and more agreements than the socially optimal network. When firms or markets are asymmetric, stable networks may involve incomplete alliances and be underconnected with respect to the social optimum.
ER  - 

